\b \cf0 Local Storage
\b0 \
\pard\tx1440\tx2160\fi720\sl288\slmult1\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 There are two parts to the Apple operating system: a group of programs which, together, make up a version of the 
\b UNIX
\b0  operating system. UNIX controls the computer. UNIX can be accessed directly through a terminal program, but that is beyond the scope of this course.\
The other part is the 
\b Graphical User Interface
\b0  (
\b GUI
\b0 ). The GUI is what you see and interact with when you use your Mac. Apple provides a basic structure for organizing information in on your computer as follows.\
\pard\tx203\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\li720\fi-504\sl288\slmult1\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \'95	Operating System (OSX)\
\pard\tx220\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\li720\fi-720\sl288\slmult1\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}System Library (hidden by default)\
{\listtext	\'95	}Applications (programs to perform specific tasks)\
{\listtext	\'95	}User Information (data)\
\pard\tx1440\tx2160\fi720\sl288\slmult1\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Each person who uses a computer has a "user name". It is possible for several people to use one computer while keeping the organization of their information structure separate. Information can be private or shared between users. We will consider a single user setup since the same principles apply to each user. \
User space contains a home folder, which will be identified as 
\b /Users/name-of-user/
\b0 . In my case, my home folder is 
\b /Users/Lewy/
\b0 , abbreviated simply as "
\b ~
\b0 ". Apple follows a typical Unix structure for storing information separately for each user, including:  \
\pard\tqr\tx1148\tx1427\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardeftab720\li1432\fi-719\ri-7923\sl288\slmult1\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}~/Applications\
{\listtext	\'95	}~/Desktop\
{\listtext	\'95	}~/Documents\
{\listtext	\'95	}~/Downloads\
{\listtext	\'95	}~/Library\
\pard\tx1440\tx2160\fi720\sl288\slmult1\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Other structure can be added, still following UNIX, but we will begin with this basic organization organization.\
