\b \cf0 Finder program\
\pard\tx1440\tx2160\fi720\sl288\slmult1\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf0 \
Apple has a good introduction to the Finder. Instead of repeating what Apple says, I encourage you to visit Apple's page, read what it offers, and follow some of the links. Finder is a powerful tool which is central to Mac systems. Please go to {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://support.apple.com/kb/PH19081?locale=en_US"}}{\fldrslt https://support.apple.com/kb/PH19081?locale=en_US}}. Read or at least skim this document and explore the links there. You can do this from home.\
Of particular importance, pay attention to the discussion of 
\b folders
\b0  and  
\b tags
\b0 . Tags are the term Apple uses. Other vendors may say 
\b labels
\b0  or 
\b keywords
\b0 . The concept is the same \'96 an identifier which can be associated with multiple files or folders. You can choose to use folders or tags 
\b or a combination
\b0  of folders and tags (recommended). Just as a document or an idea can be relevant to multiple topics or projects, a tag can be attached to multiple data items.\
\
\pard\tqr\tx1148\tx1427\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardeftab720\li1432\fi-719\ri-7923\sl288\slmult1\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls4\ilvl0\cf0 The major difference between folders and tags:\
{\listtext	\'95	}If you rely completely on folders, you need to remember the structure of your filing system and the names of folders and files. The entire path is unique. To refer to a particular file, you need the path or the names. \
{\listtext	\'95	}The alternative is a collection of tags. Any file or folder can have multiple tags which relate that folder or file to multiple other documents.\
{\listtext	\'95	}There is no reason to settle on folders or tags exclusively. Using a combination can be very effective depending on your personal style.\
\pard\tx1440\tx2160\fi720\sl288\slmult1\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
